\section{ Introduction }

Precious few exact solutions of the Navier-Stokes equations are known, but they serve to guide our thinking about fluid mechanics \citep{wang1991,wang1989,bazant2005}.  Most students first encounter the parabolic profile of Hagen-Poiseuille flow in a circular pipe or Poiseuille flow between flat plates~\citep{sutera1993}.    In these unidirectional flows, inertia plays no role, leading to a simple balance between viscous stress and the applied pressure gradient.  Some less trivial examples are shown in Fig. \ref{fig:bubbles}.

Pipe flows have been thoroughly characterized in the literature on forced convection in ducts~\citep{shah1978}, and the same mathematical problem arises in a remarkable variety of other contexts.
