\subsection{ Electrochemistry }

Here, we note that same mathematical problem also describes some problems in electrochemistry.  The steady-state electrostatic potential profile $\phi(x,y)$ satisfies Eq. ~(\ref{eq:flow}) in a planar porous electrode or electrochromic glass~\citep{biesheuvel2011,biesheuvel2012} (Fig. \ref{fig:analogies}(13)), where Dirichlet boundary conditions apply at the current collectors and Neumann boundary conditions at the separator.  This is another variation on the conducting sheet analogy, where again $k=J/\sigma$ but now $\sigma$ is the macroscopic conductivity of the phase with rate limiting transport (electronic or ionic) and $J$ is the Faradaic reaction rate, assumed to be uniform for a perfect analogy.

\subsection{ Electrokinetics }

We also note that Poisson's equation arises in three different ways in the theory of electrokinetic phenomena  ~\citep{lyklema_book_vol2,hunter_book}. Besides determining the electrostatic potential profile $\phi(x,y)$ from the charge density $\rho_e$ (i.e. electrostatics, above), it also determines the electro-osmotic flow $u=u_E(x,y)$ in response to an axial electric field with $k=\rho_e E/\mu$ (Fig. \ref{fig:analogies}(14)), as well as the streaming current $u=j_s(x,y)=\rho_e u_p(x,y)$ in response to a pressure-driven flow (Fig. \ref{fig:analogies}(15)).  A perfect analogy with uniform flow requires a constant charge density $\rho_e$, which approximates the diffuse charge profile in a nanochannel with uniform surface charge and thick, overlapping double layers.  Below, we shall also consider the more realistic case of non-uniform charge density, $\rho_e(x,y)$.





