&=& - \frac{\varepsilon}{G} \int\int (\phi - \psi) \nabla^2 u_g \; dxdy \ \ \ \mbox{ (Eq. (\ref{eq:green}))} \\
&=& - \frac{\varepsilon}{\mu} \int\int (\phi - \psi)  \; dxdy \ \ \ \mbox{ (Eq. (\ref{eq:ug}))} \\
&=& - \frac{1}{E} \int\int u_e  \; dxdy \ \ \ \mbox{ (Eq. (\ref{eq:uepsi}))} \\
&=& L_{EO}
\end{eqnarray*}
In the key step above, we perform two integrations by parts (Green's second identity),
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int\int (\nabla^2 f_1) f_2 \; dxdy &=& \oint \hat{n}\cdot(f_2 \nabla f_1 - f_1 \nabla f_2) \nonumber \\ 
& & + \int\int f_1 (\nabla^2 f_2) \; dxdy \label{eq:green}
\end{eqnarray*}
where the line integral vanishes since $f_1 = \phi-\psi=0$  and $f_2 = u_g = 0$ on the surface.


\section{ Conclusion } 

This paper provides an overview of exact solutions  and physical analogies for unidirectional flow.  Through a variety of examples, we have shown how to construct approximate geometries that admit simple exact solutions by  manipulating the harmonic homogeneous solution to Poisson's equation.  We have identified fifteen physical analogies for unidirectional flow, including many that may not have been noted before, in geological flows, electrokinetics, electrochemistry, and stochastic processes.  In these fields, the classical mathematics of unidirectional flow may find some new applications.   






